# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-72-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] There was a single international friendly between the England and Scotland national rugby union teams in the 1871–72 season.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-72-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] With no other recognised rugby union teams in Great Britain or the rest of the world, the encounter between Scotland and England represented the only possible match that could be arranged, and would continue as such until 1875, when Ireland formed their national team.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-72-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] Matches in this season were decided on goals scored.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-72-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] A goal was awarded for a successful conversion after a try, for a dropped goal or for a goal from mark.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-72-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] If a game was drawn, any unconverted tries were tallied to give a winner.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-72-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] If there was still no clear winner, the match was declared a draw.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The **rugby union match played between Scotland and England** on 27 March 1871 was the world's first international rugby match.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] It is also officially the first international football match in any football code.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The match was played at Raeburn Place, Edinburgh in front of 4,000 spectators.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] Scotland won the match, scoring two tries and a goal to England's single try.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The match resulted from a challenge issued in the sporting weekly *Bell's Weekly* on 8 December 1870 and signed by the captains of five Scottish clubs, inviting any team "selected from the whole of England" to a 20-a-side game to be played under the rugby rules.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The game was played at Raeburn Place, Edinburgh, the home ground of Edinburgh Academicals, on 27 March 1871.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The English team wore all white, with a red rose on its shirts and the Scots, brown shirts with a thistle and white cricket flannels.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The team representing England was captained by Frederick Stokes of Blackheath; that representing Scotland was led by Francis Moncrieff. the umpires were Hely Hutchinson Almond, headmaster of Loretto School in Scotland, and A.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The matches for this season were decided on goals scored.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The game, played over two halves, each of 50 minutes, was won by Scotland, who scored a goal with a successful conversion kick after grounding the ball over the goal line (permitting them to "try" to kick a goal).
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] Both sides achieved a further "try" each, but failed to convert them to goals, as the kicks were unsuccessful.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] Angus Buchanan was the first man to score a try in international rugby.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] In a return match at the Kennington Oval, London, in 1872, England were the winners.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-73-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] The **1872–73 Home Nations rugby union matches** was a single international friendly held between the England and Scotland national rugby union teams.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-73-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] With no other recognised rugby union teams in Britain or the rest of the world, the encounter between Scotland and England represented the only possible match that could be arranged, and would continue as such until 1875, when Ireland formed a national team.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 1872 association football match between the national teams of Scotland and England is officially recognised by FIFA as the first international.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It took place on 30 November 1872 at Hamilton Crescent, the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground in Partick, Glasgow.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was watched by 4,000 spectators and finished as a 0–0 draw.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Following public challenges issued in Glasgow and Edinburgh newspapers by The Football Association (FA) secretary Charles Alcock, the first encounter of five matches between teams representing England and Scotland took place in London on 5 March 1870 at The Oval, resulting in a 1–1 draw.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The second match was played on 19 November 1870, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] This was followed by matches on 25 February 1871, England 1–1 Scotland; 18 November 1871, England 2–1 Scotland; and 24 February 1872, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Most players selected for the Scottish side in these early "internationals" were from the London area, although players based in Scotland were also invited.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The only player affiliated to a Scottish club was Robert Smith of Queen's Park, Glasgow, who played in the November 1870 match and both of the 1871 games.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Robert Smith and James Smith (both of the Queen's Park club) were listed publicly for the February 1872 game, but neither played in the match.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] After the 1870 matches, there was resentment in Scotland that their team did not contain more players based in Scotland.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Alcock then proceeded to offer another challenge with a Scottish team drawn from Scotland and proposed the north of England as a venue.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] He appeared to be particularly concerned about the number of players in Scottish football teams at the time, adding: "More than eleven we do not care to play as it is with greater numbers it is our opinion the game becomes less scientific and more a trial of charging and brute force ...
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Charles W Alcock, Hon Sec of Football Association and Captain of English Eleven".
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] One reason for the absence of a formal response to Alcock's challenge may have been different football codes being followed in Scotland at the time.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] A written reply to Alcock's letter above states: "Mr Alcock's challenge to meet a Scotch eleven on the borders sounds very well and is doubtless well meant.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] But it may not be generally well known that Mr Alcock is a very leading supporter of what is called the 'association game' ... devotees of the 'association' rules will find no foemen worthy of their steel in Scotland".
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Despite this the FA were hoping to play in Scotland as early as February 1872.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In 1872, Queen's Park, as Scotland's leading club, took up Alcock's challenge, despite there being no Scottish Football Association to sanction it.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In the FA's minutes of 3 October 1872 it was noted "In order to further the interests of the Association in Scotland, it was decided that during the current season, a team should be sent to Glasgow to play a match v Scotland".
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was arranged for 30 November (St Andrew's Day), and the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground at Hamilton Crescent in Partick was selected as the venue.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] All eleven Scottish players were members of the Queen's Park, the leading Scottish club at this time, although three players were also members of other clubs; William Ker of Granville F.C. and the Smith brothers of South Norwood F.C.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland had hoped to obtain the services of Arthur Kinnaird of The Wanderers and Henry Renny-Tailyour of Royal Engineers but both were unavailable.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The teams for this match were gathered together "with some difficulty, each side losing some of their best men almost at the last moment".
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scottish side was selected by goalkeeper and captain Robert Gardner.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English side was selected by Charles Alcock and contained players from nine clubs; Alcock himself was unable to play due to injury.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match, initially scheduled for 2pm, was delayed for 20 minutes.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 4,000 spectators paid an entry fee of a shilling, the same amount charged at the 1872 FA Cup Final.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English wore caps, while the Scots wore red cowls.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match itself illustrated the advantage gained by the Queen's Park players "through knowing each others' play" as all came from the same club.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] There is no evidence in the article that the author attended the match, as the reader is clearly pointed to match descriptions in "sporting journals".
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It is also of note that the 5 March 1872 match between Wanderers and Queen's Park contains no evidence of ball passing.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] At half-time, both teams rotated the goalkeeping duties among their players: England from Robert Barker to William Maynard, and Scotland from Gardner to Robert Smith.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] On a pitch that was heavy due to the continuous rain over the previous three days, the smaller and lighter Scottish side pushed their English counterparts hard.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots had a goal disallowed in the first half after the umpires decided that the ball had cleared the tape that was used to represent the crossbar.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The latter part of the match saw the Scots defence under pressure by the heavier English forwards.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots played two full backs, two half backs and six forwards.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English played only one full back, one half back and eight forwards.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Since three defenders were required for a ball played to be onside, the English system was virtually a ready-made offside trap.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland came closest to winning the match when, in the closing stages, a Robert Leckie shot landed on top of the tape.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Though the match finished goalless, the quality of play was widely praised.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] "It was allowed to be the best game ever seen in Scotland" wrote the *Aberdeen Journal*.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The reports of the match that were published in the newspapers reveal further details of the 1872 Laws of the Game.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland won a defensive corner kick after England's attackers kicked the ball over the goal-line (a feature borrowed from Sheffield Rules but discarded in 1873).
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The throw-in was awarded to the first team to touch the ball down after it went out of play (this too would be changed in 1873); and there was a break for half-time only because no goals had been scored in the first half.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1873-74-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] The **1873–74 Home Nations rugby union matches** was a single international friendly held between the England and Scotland national rugby union teams.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1874-75-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] The **1874–75 Home Nations rugby union matches** are a series of international friendlies held between the England, Ireland and Scotland national rugby union teams.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1874-75-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] This season of games was notable as it saw the first international appearance of the Ireland team.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1875-76-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] The **1875–76 Home Nations rugby union matches** are a series of international friendlies held between the England, Ireland and Scotland national rugby union teams.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1875-76-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] These were the last international rugby games to field teams of twenty players a side, the teams reducing to fifteen a side in the 1876–77 season.
[src:1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match/1876-77-home-nations-rugby-union-matches] The **1876–77 Home Nations rugby union matches** are a series of international friendlies held between the England, Ireland and Scotland national rugby union teams.
